{"format":"tiptap/v1","updatedAt":"2026-06-21T14:42:30.819Z","doc":{"type":"doc","content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Big-O Complexity"},{"type":"text","text":" is a mathematical notation that describes how an algorithm's "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"running time"},{"type":"text","text":" (time complexity) or "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"memory usage"},{"type":"text","text":" (space complexity) grows as the "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"input size approaches infinity"},{"type":"text","text":". It provides an "},{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"asymptotic upper bound"},{"type":"text","text":", focusing on the fastest-growing term while ignoring constants and slower-growing terms. In Gen AI, Big-O is critical for understanding model scalability, optimizing inference costs, and selecting efficient algorithms for tokenization, attention mechanisms, and training."}]},{"type":"horizontalRule"},{"type":"heading","attrs":{"level":3},"content":[{"type":"text","text":"What It Is"}]},{"type":"table","content":[{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Aspect"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Definition"}]}]},{"type":"tableHeader","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Purpose"}]}]}]},{"type":"tableRow","content":[{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","marks":[{"type":"bold"}],"text":"Notation"}]}]},{"type":"tableCell","attrs":{"colspan":1,"rowspan":1,"colwidth":null,"align":null},"content":[{"type":